data.content:
**No Thread.Abort migration needed.** Your code only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — none of these APIs changed behavior in modern .NET. This code will compile and run correctly as-is on .NET 8.

**Optional modernization** (unrelated to Thread.Abort): You could simplify with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.Run`, but that's a style improvement, not a migration requirement.

```csharp
// Optional modern equivalent — not required for the migration
public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    Parallel.ForEach(items, item =>
    {
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

⚠️ One existing bug to note: your original `foreach` captures the loop variable `item` by reference. In .NET Framework with C# < 5, this caused all threads to process the *last* item. C# 5+ (which .NET 8 uses) fixed this, so it's safe now — but worth being aware of.
